`,r.jsxs(n.p,{children:["For much of the 2000s and early 2010s, many sites followed a familiar pattern: the server rendered HTML, the browser displayed it, and JavaScript improved interactivity where needed. ",r.jsx(n.strong,{children:"jQuery"})," made that layer approachable across inconsistent browsers. ",r.jsx(n.strong,{children:"WordPress"}),", ",r.jsx(n.strong,{children:"Drupal"}),", and similar CMS platforms made publishing fast for millions of sites. That stack still works for a large share of the web today."]}),`
`,r.jsxs(n.p,{children:["What changed was ",r.jsx(n.strong,{children:"user expectations"}),". Search-as-you-type, live dashboards, collaborative editing, and mobile apps raised the bar for interactivity. Teams building long-lived ",r.jsx(n.strong,{children:"applications"})," — not only articles and brochures — often adopted component-based JavaScript frameworks. ",r.jsx(n.strong,{children:"React"})," became one of the most widely used options for that job. ",r.jsx(n.strong,{children:"React Native"})," extended a similar component model to iOS and Android."]}),`
`,r.jsx(n.p,{children:"This article discusses those shifts in neutral terms. jQuery, WordPress, and React solve overlapping but not identical problems. Preferences here reflect the author's experience; your stack should match your product, team skills, and maintenance horizon."}),`
